The paper discusses pebble games in the context of proof complexity, which is a subfield of computational complexity theory. Therefore, cs.CC (Computational Complexity) is the most likely sub-category. The paper also discusses pebbling as a tool for studying proof systems, which involves data structures and algorithms, making cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) a likely sub-category as well. The paper also discusses lower bounds and trade-offs, which are topics in logic and discrete mathematics, making cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science) and cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics) likely sub-categories. Finally, the paper also discusses information theory, which makes cs.IT (Information Theory) a possible sub-category.
